 Thursday, July 08, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, July 7: The Telecom Regulatory Authority of India (Trai) today directed the access providers of telecom services to maintain the validity period of their tariff plans for a minimum period of six months. The access provider from the date of enrolment of the subscriber to a tariff plan will have to keep it active for a minimum period of six months. The amendment protects the subscribers from any increase in tariffs during the period. But the regulator has allowed the service provider to reduce tariffs at any time.																								 Mumbai, July 7: Indian Oiltanking, a subsidiary of Indian Oil, is making an open offer to acquire a 20 per cent stake held by the public in Stewarts amp; Lloyds at Rs 33 per share. The open offer comes after Tata Steel decided to divest its stake in Stewarts to the IOC subsidiary. Karvy Investor Services today informed the Bombay Stock Exchange on behalf of Indian Oiltanking. 
